The '''doctrine of exoneration of liens''' (sometimes simply referred to as "'''doctrine of exoneration'''") refers to a [[common law]] rule. The rule says that encumbrances (i.e. a [[mortgage law|mortgage]]) of a property conveyed by a [[Will (law)|will]] is discharged with funds from the originating [[Estate (law)|estate]], not from the property itself.<ref name=WT&E> {{Citation | last = Johanson | first = Stanley M. | last2 = Dukeminier | first2 = Jesse | title = Wills, Trusts, and Estates | publisher = Aspen Law & Business | year = 2000 | page = 468 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=-Aelkpuz5jsC&q=%22doctrine+of+exoneration+of+liens%22&dq=%22doctrine+of+exoneration+of+liens%22&ei=MwJ6S_W2MonEywSpg9WfBA&client=firefox-a&cd=1 | isbn = 0-7355-0636-1}} </ref>
